      <hedline>
        <hl1>Straight to the Bank</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Ernest M Fishman letter, commenting on William Safire's Sept 7 column on protecting one's identity, says Social Security recipients should have their checks deposited directly into their accounts through a federal funds transfer</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Guarding Your Identity,'' by William Safire (column, Sept. 7):</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Guarding Your Identity,'' by William Safire (column, Sept. 7):</p>
        <p>The 14 million Social Security recipients who are getting monthly checks in envelopes with smaller windows to hide their Social Security numbers are hardly protected from theft of identity just because opening the envelope is a federal crime.</p>
        <p>The only sure protection against this thievery is getting direct deposit into a bank account through a federal funds transfer. The process is easy to set up, and many banks offer free checking accounts.</p>
        <p>ERNEST M. FISHMAN  Treadwell, N.Y., Sept. 7, 2000</p>
      </block>
